TextBlock.TextLine: London m Henry Maynand
mij last to you was on the 14 curr. to which referre you sence rec. yd of 27 30
past, which bring mee the good news of yd safe arrival in london, for which am
vere gladd, as also that cloth is falles & more plentifull, besides better conditioned
as last yeare which I hope to finde so, whes y goods in ordered are here, in
themeane while one fathers resints want the a 1 selver mancks, before caster
there fore pray governe yd self accordingly, I hope them will fall as also other
pack whites, which I sould be gladd to know, wee have hadd these a fill
frost, so that all rivers here are innaigable, which will keep our sent time
backward a give us butt in considecable sale before caster, whoever please to
procied with all possible care in the desired goods, of which do expect yd. advise
from time to time, as for the wessenre bustiynes I'll delay that yett for some
time, or nather few months to cleare the better what is depending on some
other acctt. I have discoursed some freinds about heary goods, of which my
vere good freind mr. Daniel Busschop told mee he would make atry all
to baew, which I I hath not already writte you, will write next, though I told
hhm, you & I would have come to seesm had time permitted, so itt would not
be a miss, would you waite him a letter in dutch or french, he is avere able, &
good man & exfrwamly obliging to him that serves him to content mr. John
merten elhus hath been & is hes great freind, as also good honeft pancius
miller to yd gov, what I can do in yd behalf shall be don befallibly
I must pay some monyes for m. Warnes thes week, I supose I do itt safely
so shall remitt you the valeu prext, & hope to roewd, to bring all to yd content
though as yett there is no mny sturring. I have a small commission from
mr. Will. sealy from exon, whoo is recommanded domee by m. Gardnes & Comp
by advise of yd self to sard gardnes, m sealy beeng innell uncanowne
to mee pray betwipt ns give mee yd. opinnon I first
a 18 d
Londen mr. Henry Collier
mij last to you was on the 11 cur to which refenre you, sence recd. yd of 30 past
& 3 cur the prodigions Imindations every where here abouts will breake many ones
heart, the citter of Hulst is al most daiver avay, for the water came in one gate
& did nun out the other & drove, or toth with itt boath housed, & the gates itt self
& most past of the fortifications, & made al most ariver in the midst of the towne,
for 4 sorts of sea fish is cought upon the mankest there, itt is not to be disenbed as
itt is. John Button complaines heavely, yett I supese he is houest, for I trust
hun now & then for a small matter which he comes shont, & he doth his ende avoir
to pay in good termes, & sayes opentley, that itt is half his mine, butt that he will
satissies every boddy, sence the smimdations he hath payd yd. bill besides £32- for my
acctt. so that I hope you will not loose by hum & could wish IH. was as able, or
willing to satisfie you, yd bill of £130- must accept, seeng itt will be the last for
centaine as for laces I am not accquainted with black or couloured, butt onely
white, I thinck black comes from about lille, butt cullond I know not, behoever
I could butt daye with a little, for I am altoghethes to serve freinds, where in soever
if I can butt do itt I sanck you for yd favour in my behalfe by m. warner
as for mathers I am gladd you have 20 bales, butt in constience I could wish you hadd
200- & then I would not advise you to sell for £5 st so you may vere well make
the most of the 20 you have for I doubt I shall not be able to help you to any more
the letters came butt last night, so do not know if I shall be able to see John
Buttor before to marrow, hen is 2 bales in towne butt non of the best I mught
have them for 32- d there is mathers att hille, & about srambbourgh, where
there hath been also mundation butt whoever there might come some franthence
sheard one say this day, that mathers were sold the crabb att ƒ80- butt that a
parcell comme from hambrough made them fall to ƒ60- a god, what I can do
for you shall be don
a 18 febo 1682
London mr. Edmund Warner
mj last to you was on the 11 cur. sence recd. yd. of 30 past, inclosed you have nroyce
foo 4 packetts of laces, which is all I have provided & bought for yd. acctt most past
is halfe for nothing, so that god sending them well, I hope they will prove to good content
Ill send forward with every nosfanger one, for newport, where N.16. must be arrived
yeasterday: I hope n. 11.12. 13 & 14 with you by this thime, please to examin
these envoyces & finding right give mee credit for £255„19„4 flemish, I thought ex. would
ise, butt itt is sehely to fall, so shall endeavour to dispose to the valew to yd most
advantage & do my utt most to serve you to content in all: laces continew yett cheap
much against everj ones exspectation, so shall ende avour to pick up now & then a
penny worth assorted as the dayly orders I receave from london, whilst you please
to examin all, & give mee yd. opinion, that I might be able to serve you well
a 16d
London m. Will: Sebb
Leyen mr Will: Sealy
I finde my self heonoud with yd of 28 past, where by you desire I hinw ho sondred
waight of the beste new cloter grace seed, if to be had att 3 a 34 butt att 3½
½ onely swentw ho findred & if good old seed for about 2 J, I hope shall be
able to send you of boath, though itt is some what issen of late, itt is boughs
on the pays de waes from whinee wee bring itt to Gant & shom thenme to Bruges,
where speedly a vessel from yd parts with serges is exspected, the charges are
vere irconsiderable, for itt payeses no duties outward, so that the way of ostend
or Bruges is the best or cheapese, for itt miust pay charges in holland of coming
fort going out, so to my advise shall dispatch itt by way of ostend if i can meet
with the parell to content, of which you shall have the needfull advise
mnsterdam de hulter en van hopimerigh
mens sedert dat ick aen u.l sijn rekeninghe courant hebbe
gesonden geen van ul vernomen echter verhopen de selve
ul is gevoorden ende daer over het accort sult hebben gevonden
desen pripalijck om ul te adviseren dat alle sorten van
boter present in groete demande sijn soo waerhet sacks de
u tot brugh& niet en was verkocht, ofte dat uu bbe costi
eenighe bij hadde een goede maert voor de selve soude
connen becomen sijn de van differete des wegens
aengepocht met een letter aentwwrt sal u verobligeren
